<h2>Florida Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Florida offers several attractive incentives and rebates that significantly reduce the cost of solar panel installations and energy-efficient HVAC systems, making these investments more accessible and financially beneficial for homeowners and businesses throughout the state.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal Solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC):</strong> The federal government provides a 30% tax credit for solar panel installations completed through 2032, allowing property owners to deduct 30% of the total system cost from their federal tax liability. This credit applies to equipment, installation labor, and related expenses, with no cap on the credit amount. The credit steps down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034 before expiring for residential installations.</li>

<li><strong>Florida Solar and CHP Sales Tax Exemption:</strong> Florida exempts solar energy systems from state sales tax, providing immediate savings of 6-7.5% on equipment purchases. This exemption applies to solar panels, inverters, batteries, and installation materials, reducing upfront costs by \$800-2,000 on typical residential installations.</li>

<li><strong>Property Tax Exemption for Renewable Energy:</strong> Florida Statute 196.175 provides a 100% property tax exemption for solar energy systems installed on residential and commercial properties. This exemption means that adding solar panels will not increase property tax assessments, despite potentially increasing home values by \$15,000-25,000 or more.</li>

<li><strong>Florida Power & Light (FPL) Programs:</strong> FPL offers net metering agreements allowing solar customers to receive credit for excess energy production at retail rates. The utility also provides rebates for energy-efficient HVAC equipment, smart thermostats, and home energy audits through their conservation programs, with rebates ranging from \$50-500 depending on equipment type and efficiency ratings.</li>

<li><strong>Local Utility Rebates:</strong> Municipal utilities throughout Florida, including Orlando Utilities Commission (OUC), Gainesville Regional Utilities (GRU), and others, offer additional rebates and incentives for solar installations and energy-efficient equipment. These programs vary by utility but can provide rebates of \$500-2,000 for qualifying solar installations and \$100-300 for high-efficiency HVAC upgrades.</li>

<li><strong>PACE Financing:</strong> Many Florida counties participate in Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) financing programs, allowing property owners to finance solar and energy efficiency improvements through property tax assessments. This financing option provides long-term, low-interest funding with payments tied to the property rather than the individual owner.</li>
</ul>

